DEM manipulation and GIS workflow

The objective is to capture and transform DEM data into a CSV file that will later be use to set a bunch of properties for Lecode simulation.
The data manipulation preserves the georeferencing information of the DEM, allowing later projection of the model in a GIS client (or google earth).

Workflow description:

  1. Download a DEM from the web (grid in lat/long coordinates),
  2. Test the scene projection with GDAL,
  3. Re-project the subset to UTM with GDAL in order to have a GeoTIF with pixels location in m,
  4. Crop the new projection and export the DEM at a selected resolution in a xyz format (in m),
  5. Perform the transformation to LECODE input format,
  6. Analyse DEM for better definition of LECODE XmL input parameters.

1. Download a DEM from the web

Example of DEM providers:

  • NOAA ETOPO1 (~1 km resolution)
  • CGIAR SRTM (90 m DEM)
  • OGPs EPSG Geodetic Parameter Datase
  • needs to be extended...

After downloading the DEM, upload it to the Dropbox SGFM-data folder.

Note:
To be granted access to this folder you will need to send a request to SGFM support team.

By uploading your DEM to the SGFM dropbox share folder, it will be directly accessible by the SGFM IP[y] Server for further processing.
IMPORTANT:
  • There is a limited number of space available on the SGFM dropbox share folder and you will have to remove your uploaded files after completion of the workflow.
  • The iPython Notebook that you are editing however will be saved and you shoud be able to recreate your SGFM input just by uploading your files to the server.
  • To facilitate this process we strongly recommend that you provide within your notebook some information on the uploaded DEM such as the name of the provider, the region extent, the projection references...

For the present notebook we used a SRTM ArcInfo ASCII from CGIAR:
  • Product: SRTM 90m DEM version 4
  • Data File Name: srtm_63_18.zip
  • Mask File Name: srtm_mk_63_18.zip
  • Latitude min: 30 S, max: 25 S
  • Longitude min: 130 E, max: 135 E
  • Center point: Latitude 27.50 S, Longitude 132.50 E


Note:
Once on the server, your file will be accessible in the notebook via: 
../SGFM-data/your_file_name

2. Test the scene projection with GDAL

First get information of the uploaded file and read general information about the upoaded file using gdalinfo. It will report all of the following (if known):

  • The format driver used to access the file.
  • Raster size (in pixels and lines).
  • The coordinate system for the file (in OGC WKT).
  • The geotransform associated with the file (rotational coefficients are currently not reported).
  • Corner coordinates in georeferenced, and if possible lat/long based on the full geotransform (but not GCPs).
  • Ground control points.
  • File wide (including subdatasets) metadata.
  • Band data types.
  • Band color interpretations.
  • Band block size.
  • Band descriptions.
  • Band min/max values (internally known and possibly computed).
  • Band checksum (if computation asked).
  • Band NODATA value.
  • Band overview resolutions available.
  • Band unit type (i.e.. "meters" or "feet" for elevation bands).
  • Band pseudo-color tables.

Note:
If the projection information is only required use the GetProjectionRef() function. This function which returns the projection reference as a WKT string. It shows the image geodetic system (here WGS 84) and other projection information such as unit, orgin, extent and ownership.

3. Re-project the subset to UTM

Now we re-project the image to UTM coordinate system in order to have the pixel location in metres.
To convert to Universal Transverse Mercator (UTM), gdalwarp requires the UTM zone of your image. You can use EPSG registry webinterface to check if your UTM zone is correct. Using the registry you will:

  • first use the Show Map button and select your area of interest.
  • then in the Type box choose Coordinate Reference System / Projected CRS and for the Name put the current GIS (here WGS 84), and click Search
  • a table will appear, look to find within the Area Description column which one contains your simulation domain and use the corresponding Code in your gdalwarp function.
Then you can use gdalinfo to check that the re-projection works fine.

4. Clip the region to the extent of the simulation area

Now that the DEM has been projected in UTM, we will crop it to fit with the extent of the region that we want to simulate with Lecode.
In this notebook we want to define a region of 80 km large , 100 km long centered around the following coordinates (132,-28) using a resolution of 200 m but oriented 30 degrees from west.
The long/lat coordinates is projected in the correct coordinate system using PyProj library.
Then for illustration purposes we display it on the map with a marker.

In [45]: 
from pyproj import Proj
#p=Proj(proj='utm',zone=10,ellps='WGS84')
p = Proj(proj='utm',zone='52S',ellps='WGS84')
p.srs

Using Shapefile Library we will create a shapefile to the extent of the simulation area that will be use later to crop the region.

In [47]: 
import shapefile
from shapely.geometry import box
w = shapefile.Writer(shapefile.POLYGON)

# Simulation lenght, width & orientation
# Define the simulation lenght & width of the simulation area (in metres) and the rotation angle from west (in degrees)
lg=80000
wd=100000
angle=math.radians(330)

# Define simulation region corners
coordinates = []
# SE point
tx = ox-lg/2
ty = oy-wd/2
corner_x = cos(angle)*(tx-ox)-sin(angle)*(ty-oy)+ox
corner_y = sin(angle)*(tx-ox)+cos(angle)*(ty-oy)+oy
point1 = [corner_x,corner_y]

# SW point
tx = ox+lg/2
ty = oy-wd/2
corner_x = cos(angle)*(tx-ox)-sin(angle)*(ty-oy)+ox
corner_y = sin(angle)*(tx-ox)+cos(angle)*(ty-oy)+oy
point2 = [corner_x,corner_y]

# NW point
tx = ox+lg/2
ty = oy+wd/2
corner_x = cos(angle)*(tx-ox)-sin(angle)*(ty-oy)+ox
corner_y = sin(angle)*(tx-ox)+cos(angle)*(ty-oy)+oy
point3 = [corner_x,corner_y]

# NE point
tx = ox-lg/2
ty = oy+wd/2
corner_x = cos(angle)*(tx-ox)-sin(angle)*(ty-oy)+ox
corner_y = sin(angle)*(tx-ox)+cos(angle)*(ty-oy)+oy
point4 = [corner_x,corner_y]

# Merge points
coords = [point1, point2, point3, point4]
segments = [coords]

# Create the shapefile
w.poly(parts = segments)
w.field('FIRST_FLD','C','40')
w.record('First','Polygon')
w.save('../SGFM-data/srtm_63_18/poly_shape')

We then use Fatiando library to define a regular grid used in Lecode

In [51]: 
ifile = '../SGFM-data/srtm_63_18/dem_shape.csv'
x,y,z = loadtxt( ifile, skiprows=0, delimiter=',', unpack = True)

# Extensions
hext = int( ( xmax - xmin ) / dx )
vext = int( ( ymax - ymin ) / dx )

# Be careful the shape is defined as ( ny, nx )
shape = ( int( vext )+1, int( hext )+1 )

# Interpolation
gx, gy, gz = gridder.interp( x, y, z, shape, area=(gxmin, gxmax, gymin, gymax) , algorithm='cubic', extrapolate=True)
savetxt('../SGFM-data/srtm_63_18/dem_reg.csv',column_stack((gx, gy, gz)), fmt='%g', delimiter=' ')

5. Perform the transformation to Lecode input format

In this step we will generate the topographic and initial deposit files for Lecode simulation based on the clipped and rotated area.
First we create an ASCII grid that will be used during the export process. Then lecode_basic_input script will create the required Lecode files. 


lecode_basic_input name_ascii_grid thickness_init_layer nb_material_type init_layer_hardness
The script requires 3 parameters and an optional one:
  • name_ascii_grid name of the ASCII grid generated using gdal_translate
  • thickness_init_layer thickness of the initial sedimentary layer in metres,
  • nb_material_type number of sediments that will be defined in Lecode XmL input file,
  • init_layer_hardness is optional (default is 1) and enable the definition of a hardness value for basement sedimentary layer.

In [52]: 
import os, sys

# Create an ASCII grid from the regular grid obtained using Fatiando library
'''
Use the csv_2_asc script to perform format transformation:
        - the first argument is the CSV file from Fatiando library
        - second argument is the number of columns (W/E direction)
        - third argument is the number of rows (S/N direction)
        
The script returns a file with the same name as the input file but with the asc extension
'''
os.system('csv_2_asc ../SGFM-data/srtm_63_18/dem_reg.csv 401 501')


"""
Perform the transformation to LECODE input format using lecode_basic_input script
     - first argument is the ASCII grid you've just generated
     - second argument is the thickness of the initial sedimentary layer
     - third argument is the number of sediment classes (they will be distribute evenly over the sedimentary layer)
     - last argument is the layer hardness
"""
os.system('lecode_basic_input ../SGFM-data/srtm_63_18/dem_reg.asc 50 5 10')
print "LECODE input have been created, check for .nodes & .dep files"

LECODE input have been created, check for .nodes & .dep files

6. Analyse DEM for better definition of Lecode XmL input parameters

DEM relief

To have a look at the elevation range you can use gdalinfo command with the mm option and search within the answer for Computed Min/Max.
Then use the gdaldem function with the color-relief option.
Base on the range you can define a text color scale file (some predefined color scales are proposed in the color-scale Dropbox folder) to produce a PNG file of the clipped region.

DEM slope

To produce the DEM slope we use gdaldem function again with slope option and the -p option as well which specifies that the calculated slope will be expressed as percent slope.
Again to check the slope range you can use gdalinfo function with the mm option and search within the output for Computed Min/Max.
Base on the range you can define a text color scale file (some predefined color scales are proposed in the color-scale foler for the slope) to produce a PNG file of the clipped region slope.

In [54]:

Flow accumulation map

LECODE uses flow accumulation maps to defined several parameters such as the adaptive TIN resolution or to trigger mass movements (see website for more information).

The next step will create the initial flow accumulation map that could be use to define these parameters in the XmL input file.

In [55]: 
import os, sys

'''
Perform Planchon fill depression algorithm using the fill_depression script
        - first argument is the ASCII grid created in step 5,
        - second argument is the output file name a depressionless ASCII grid.
        - third argument is the parameter used to remove the flat and hole areas. 
        
Ref: Planchon, O., and F., Darboux (2001). 
    A fast, simple and versatile algorithm to fill the depressions of digital elevation models. 
    Catena, 46, 159176. 
'''
os.system('fill_depression ../SGFM-data/srtm_63_18/dem_reg.asc ../SGFM-data/srtm_63_18/demshape.asc 0.001')

'''
Run the multiple flow direction script flow_acc
        - first argument is the depressionless ASCII grid created above
        - second argument is the flow accumulation ASCII grid.
        
'''
os.system('flow_acc ../SGFM-data/srtm_63_18/demshape.asc ../SGFM-data/srtm_63_18/facc_reg.asc')
